{"timestamp": "2025-12-02 15:51:29.133086", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — network health assessment\n\nScope and approach\n- Focus: detect anomalies, localize faulty device(s), identify root cause(s).\n- Data sources used: global reachability matrix, host interface/config dumps, DHCP lease file, dhcp relay process listing, FRR (OSPF) route and OSPF process outputs on distribution / server-access routers.\n- No mitigations or remediation steps are proposed here — only findings.\n\nExecutive summary\n- The overall routed fabric and OSPF appear healthy: FRR routers have expected OSPF adjacencies and routes for 10.1.x, 10.2.x and server networks (10.200.0.0/24). Most hosts can reach servers (DNS, load balancer, web servers) and the DHCP server.\n- One clear anomaly: host_2_1_1_1 has no IPv4 address and is not receiving DHCP service. This makes the host unable to participate in IP connectivity (many pings originating from it are “unknown”).\n- Evidence indicates the DHCP relay (dhcrelay) is running on router_dist_2_1 and forwarding to the central DHCP server, so the outage is likely at DHCP-server configuration for that subnet (missing/incorrect DHCP pool or subnet declaration) or otherwise the DHCP server is not assigning addresses for 10.2.1.0/24 (the network attached to host_2_1_1_1). Other DHCP-served subnets are being assigned normally.\n\nDetailed findings and evidence\n\n1) Host host_2_1_1_1 — no IP address (primary fault)\n- Observation: host_2_1_1_1's network stack shows eth0 up but no IPv4 address and no routes:\n  - ifconfig: eth0 is UP but no \"inet\" entry.\n  - ip addr: eth0 has no inet.\n  - ip route: empty.\n- Reachability evidence: in the reachability matrix many pings sourced from host_2_1_1_1 returned status \"unknown\" (no tx/rx results), consistent with the host not having an IP.\n- DHCP lease evidence: the DHCP server lease file (/var/lib/dhcp/dhcpd.leases) contains many leases (10.1.x and 10.2.2.x, etc.) but no active lease for host_2_1_1_1 (no entry for its hostname or MAC).\n- Conclusion: host_2_1_1_1 has not obtained a DHCP lease and therefore has no IPv4 address.\n\n2) DHCP relay on router_dist_2_1 — running and active (not faulty)\n- Process listing shows dhcrelay running on router_dist_2_1:\n  - dhcrelay -i br0 -i eth0 10.200.0.8\n- router_dist_2_1 br0 has IP 10.2.1.1 (connected network) and eth0 to upstream (172.16.0.11) — config consistent with relaying DHCP from that VLAN to central DHCP server.\n- Route table on router_dist_2_1 shows 10.2.1.0/24 is connected (br0) and 10.200.0.0/24 reachable via upstream, so relay forwarding path exists.\n\n3) DHCP server behavior / configuration (likely issue)\n- The DHCP server lease file shows extensive lease activity for many subnets (10.1.1.x, 10.2.2.x, 10.1.2.x, etc.) but no leases for 10.2.1.x (subnet where host_2_1_1_1 sits).\n- Given the relay is running and most other DHCP-served subnets receive addresses, the likely cause is the DHCP server either:\n  - has no subnet declaration/pool for 10.2.1.0/24, or\n  - is configured to ignore requests with giaddr 10.2.1.1, or\n  - has exhausted/disabled that pool.\n- There is no evidence in the data collected that the relay is blocking DHCP requests — the relay process is present and other hosts served by relays are receiving leases.\n\n4) OSPF and routing — generally healthy\n- server_access_router and the distribution/core routers show OSPF routes for the relevant subnets (10.1.x, 10.2.x, 10.200.0.0/24) and directly-connected networks where expected.\n- Example: server_access_router shows 10.200.0.0/24 directly connected and backbone routes to 10.1.x and 10.2.x via 172.16.0.14.\n- No OSPF LSAs/external issues were observed in the provided OSPF status excerpt.\n\n5) Backend web servers (20.200.0.x) — expected inaccessibility\n- The reachability matrix shows the backend web addresses in the 20.200.0.0/24 range are not directly reachable from user hosts (many entries \"unknown\" for 20.200.0.x). This matches the network design: backend web servers are intentionally non-routable from user host subnets (they are in a separate backend network reachable only via the load balancer).\n- This behavior is expected and not an anomaly.\n\nLocalization of fault(s)\n- Primary affected device: host_2_1_1_1 (no IPv4).\n- Network element(s) to investigate further (likely root cause located here):\n  - DHCP server (dhcp_server): missing or misconfigured subnet/pool for 10.2.1.0/24 or pool exhausted/disabled.\n  - Router hosting the DHCP relay (router_dist_2_1): relay is present and listening on br0; evidence does not implicate the relay itself as broken, but the relay/giaddr interaction could be validated by checking DHCP request logs on the DHCP server to confirm it receives DISCOVERs with giaddr 10.2.1.1.\n- Switch/access layer: switch_access_2_1_1 shows interfaces up and RX/TX activity; physical link between host_2_1_1_1 and the switch appears up at L2 (eth0 shows RX/TX), so physical connectivity is present. The problem is at IP/DHCP allocation, not a down link.\n\nRoot-cause hypothesis (most likely)\n- The DHCP server is not issuing leases for the 10.2.1.0/24 subnet (where host_2_1_1_1 lives). Evidence:\n  - host_2_1_1_1 has no IP and no lease entry.\n  - dhcrelay is running on router_dist_2_1, so client requests should be forwarded.\n  - DHCP lease file contains leases for many other subnets but no 10.2.1.x leases.\n- Likely causes on the DHCP server side:\n  - Missing subnet declaration/pool for 10.2.1.0/24.\n  - Misconfigured pool (zero available addresses, disabled, or mis-bound).\n  - DHCP server policy/config filters preventing allocation for giaddr 10.2.1.1.\n- Less likely (but possible) alternate causes:\n  - DHCP requests are not reaching the DHCP server (but other relayed subnets reach it, and relay is running => less likely).\n  - Host-specific issues (e.g., host DHCP client broken) — but host shows tx/rx frames and no DHCP lease attempts appear